MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Atmospheric Entry lesson! This is an involved lesson that covers many systems working together to bring the Command Module through the atmosphere.
You are currently in a ~160 nmi x ~160 nmi circular orbit around the Earth.

During entry, the attitude of the craft is important. We need to ensure that our heat shield is facing the direction of flight, while also having a good control of roll. Roll is what we will use to control how the craft flies through the atmosphere.
The first thing we will do is the perform the SPS burn in retrograde direction. Please open the MISSION PAD and open the SPS DEORBIT & ENTRY checklist.

We will use P30 to set up the burn and P40 to perform the burn. I recommend referencing to the AGC chapter in the manual, following the steps for P30 and P40 while going through this lesson. Once the de-orbit burn is complete you will get quite busy with procedures.
Before we continue, please know this lesson will go through the basic steps needed to land. The process is so involved that I think it's best to learn the major tasks needed first.
Once you know those, you should be able to practice using the checklists and perform the more realistic procedures. But use the checklist as a reference throughout the lesson.

Open the CSM Burn Planner and plan an entry burn with an entry interface angle of about 2 degrees. Set the phase to 260, the dV to 475, the direction to RETROGRADE. Take a note of the "Time of CM/SM sep" time stamp, then press REQUEST.
Stop and set the EVENT TIMER to 59:59, then set the mode to count down. We will use the Event Timer to count down to SM/CM separation.

The SM/CM separation should happen 12 minutes before Entry Interface (EI). Take the "Time of CM/SM sep" from the Burn Planner and subtract 1 hour from it, and take a note of the result. If "Time of CM/SM sep" was 002:43:07, then the Event Timer should start at 001:43:07. We will get back to this soon.
When ready, start program 30 using V37E 30E.
P30 should start by displaying V06 N33. The three registers will show the time to ignition in hours, minutes and seconds.
You can change these values but the burn tool should have uplinked the correct values.
Press PRO.
When ready, P30 will display V06N81, the Impulsive Delta V at TIG in Local Vertical Coordinates.
This is used to set the amount of delta V burn in a vector format, allowing the burn to happen in a given direction. We wish to burn in the retrograde direction.
The value is already populated by Mission Control after using the burn tool. You can ignore the minor differences.
Press PRO to accept the values. The computer will spend a few seconds on calculations before displaying V06N42.
V06N42 shows the Ap and Pe altitude, and the magnitude of the dV burn. Our Pe should be negative as we target a burn to bring our craft through the atmosphere. Press PRO to continue.
V16N45 is now displayed, and shows the time to ignition in R2.
Press PRO to accept, the AGC will now automatically start P00.
Next we need to orient the spacecraft into the correct burn attitude.
We will use automaneuvering to get into our attitude but let us first align the Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) - the system responsible for maintaining our stable inertial platform.
Since the ORDEAL is set to INRTL, what we see on the FDAI 1 and FDAI 2 instruments is the platform of the IMU (FDAI 1) and the platform of the GDC (FDAI 2).
We will use Program 52 to align our platform with the burn direction. The computer knows about this platform as it was uplinked when you requested the burn.
Key V37E 52E on the DSKY. The program will spend some seconds loading before showing V04 N06.

We will use Program 52, option 1 to align the IMU with the "Preferred" orientation. The "Preferred" orientation is the one uplinked to your computer when you requested the burn. These orientations are named Reference to Stable Member Matrix (REFSMMAT).
Key V22E +1E on the DSKY. Verify that R2 shows +00001, then press [PRO].
When VERB 06 NOUN 22 shows, press [PRO] on the DSKY to complete the alignment and torque the IMU. This will also take you back to P00. Next we will automaneuver.

To do this, we will use V49E. This will load R62, the routine used for auto-maneuvering. As our IMU is aligned with the burn direction, set R1, R2 and R3 to +00000. Follow the (V49) CREW DEF MNVR checklist and complete the routine as you did in the auto-maneuvering lesson.
When the spacecraft is in the correct attitude, open the Mission Pad and follow the "(P40) G&N SPS Thrusting" checklist to execute the burn. You can either RUN it or follow it manually.

P40 is now running. This will show V50 N18. Verb 50 Noun 18 means Request Maneuver: Desired FDAI Auto-maneuver Attitude. Please note that when you press PRO, V06 will display as the manuver is executed.
The maneuver is complete when V50 is displayed again. Press PRO again when the maneuver is complete to fine align. V06 should again display.
V50 N18 is flashing again, press ENTER to break the automaneuver routine and continue with the P40 program flow.
V50 N25 if now flashing with R1 set to 00204, meaning Please Perform: Checklist Item: 204.
Time scale until the one hour before CM/SM Sep we calculated earlier (in my case it was 001:43:16) and start the Event Timer. It should count down towards SM/CM sep.
Then time scale again to about 20 minutes (002:20:00) minutes before the planned ignition time (you can use the MET timer and compare it with the Burn Planner: TIG field).
Returning to Checklist Item: 204: Complete the gimbal check per SPS thrusting checklist, P40 will show V06 N40 when it is complete.
V06 N40 now shows the time to ignition, dV to be gained and the accumulated velocity. Continue with the checklist.
When the countdown shows that it's 35 seconds left, the registers will blank for 5 seconds to indicate the burn is close.
When it's 5 seconds left, V99 N40 is displayed. This means that the astronaut approval is needed to execute the burn. Press PRO to accept.
Once PRO is pressed, and the SPS is armed, and the countdown reaches zero, the burn will execute.
V06 N40 will again display, showing the status of the burn.
The engine will automatically stop when the burn is complete, and R2 should show zero, or a fraction below zero.
Complete the checklist. Press ROGER when the checklist is complete.

Let us also prepare the Earth Landing System now, the system responisble for releaseing our chutes. Insert the two ELS fuses on the left hand MDC-8 panel (the lowest row of fuses). Close ELS Bat A first.
Then close the ELS BAT B.
Then ARM the ELS LOGIC on MDC-1, it's a protected switch. This will make the ELS ready. This lesson will prepare this now as you will get quite busy after entry.
Next we will prepare for Reentry.

Next we will use Program 52 again to align the IMU with the "horizon" at the Entry Interface point. The Entry Interface (EI) is a point of our trajectory where our altitude is 400.000 ft. This point marks the beginning of our atmospheric entry.

First of all, let us find our ENTRY PAD form. Open CREW MEMBERS -> REQUEST PADS & CHARTS -> OPEN ETNRY PAD FORM to do this. (I recommend using a tablet or a printed version of this form, in-game method is just a backup for those who do not have this)

Let us find the time of our Entry Interface (EI) passing. Again, from CREW MEMBERS -> REQUEST PADS & CHARTS, press the REQUEST ENTRY PAD button. This will show you the ENTRY PARAMETERS. Fill out the form.
The parameter we are looking for is a time value named RRT and should be a value close to 002:55:35, depending on your deorbit burn.
Next we will align to the "horizon" (Local Vertical Local Horizon) at Entry Interface (EI). The RRT value can be used as the time stamp.
Key [VERB] [3] [7] [ENTR] [5] [2] [ENTR] to start P52.
Wait for VERB 04 NOUN 06.
Then key V22W +2E. Verify R2 is set to +00002, then press [PRO].

Now VERB 06 NOUN 34 shows. This wants you to input a time stamp in MET. It could be any time in the future and will align the IMU to the estimated Local Vertical Local Horizon (LVLH) at that time. We want to input our time of EI-passing here.

Use V25E to enter the time of EI (RRT) on your ENTRY PAD. My value was 002:55:35 but use the one you received. In my case, R1=+00002, R2=+00055, R3=+03500. When complete, press [PRO] to proceed, and then [PRO] again to align.
Press GDC ALIGN to then align the GDC with the IMU (this is the simplified procedures activated when the ATT SET switch on MDC-1 is set to IMU - feel free to use the realistic procedures too).

The EMS needs to be set up as well. Set the function to RNG SET, then set RANGE to the RTGO EMS parameter from your ENTRY PAD. To do this, press INC on the dV/EMS SET thumb switch until the RANGE field is equal. You can press and hold higher or lower on the switch to increase the step pace.
Good. Set the function to V0 Set, then set V0 to the 25500 line. To do this, press INC on the dV/EMS SET thumb switch a few times so the script line is aligned with the display line.
If you look at the PAD, the parameter VI0 shows where the line should be aligned. For lunar entry, this is much higher. For now, you can leave it on the line and if desired, tweak it slightly.
Set the ENTRY EMS 0.05g switch to UP to ARM the EMS.
Then set the EMS mode to ENTRY and keep it in STBY.

Next, use V49E to set up an automaneuver to the target EI attitude, this can be found in the ENTRY PAD (0, 209, 0) - then start the manuever. Do not wait until the manuever is complete, use V34E to stop the routine.
The initial program to prepare for entry is P61, the Entry Preparation program.
On the CMC, run V37E 61E to start the entry preparations.
The first input will be the predicted latitude and longitude of the splashdown location, and the last is if the initial entry will be heads up (+1) or heads down (-1). This controls the lift vector.
The capsule has been designed to have an aerodynamic lift vector, and is opposite of the direction of the heads. So if the heads are pointing down, the vector points up.
This vector is used to maneuver the capsule during entry, just like an aeroplane.
Press PRO to accept the default values.
Next, V06N60 shows predictions for entry, like the predicted g-force, velocity at entry interface and flight path angle between the inertial velocity and the local horizontal at the entry interface.
The entry interface is at around 400k of altitude.
Press PRO to accept the values. The next screen shows more predictions like range to go from 0.05g, the predicted velocity at 0.05g and time until 0.05g.
Press PRO to accept. P61 now automatically moves to P62 - the CM/SM Separation and Preentry Maneuver.
P62 first displays V50N25, with 41 in R1. This means Please Perform: Checklist item: 41. This is CM/SM separation.
Check the SPS DEORBIT & ENTRY CHECKLIST, section 30.
The CM RCS system needs to be enabled, as the SM RCS system will be jettisoned soon. Verify that the CM RCS LOGIC is set to ON.
Set the CM RCS Propellant 1 system on MDC-2 to ARM (UP).
Do the same for the CM RCS Propellant 2 system. The CM RCS system will now automatically be ready when the SM is jettisoned.
Then pressurize the CM RCS by setting the CM RCS PRESS switch to up. This requires that the pyros are armed.
Set the SC CONT to SCS.
Then we will need change our power source. So far in this mission, the Fuel Cells has been the primary source of power.
Since these are located in the Service Module, we will loose them when we separate it. The Entry and Post Landing batteries will take over as the primary power source.
These are located inside the Command Module. To tie them to the Main Bus, set the Main Bus Tie A/C switch to UP.
Do the same for the Main Bus Tie B/C switch, set it to UP.
The batteries should now be powering the Command Module.
Next, we will configure the C&WS to not throw master alarms due to warnings from the SM. Switch the C&WS mode from CSM to CM.
We will now perform the SM-separation. Switch to CMC - FREE and manually YAW the craft 45 degrees to the right. Then set the CM/SM Sep switch 1 to UP.
Then, set the CM/SM Sep switch 2 to UP.
The SM is now separated and drifting away from the Command Module.
Press PRO on the computer.
This activates the entry DAP and once again displays predicted landing point and gives you an opportunity to select the initial lift vector.
Use the view selector to move the view to the COMMANDERS WINDOW, set the controls to manual and correct the attitude so you are facing head down, and the FDAI is showing the target PGNS attitude.
A the line crossing the entire window at 31.7 degrees indicates the relative angle between the horizon and the X-axis of the spacecraft. The horizon should be within 5 degrees from this line.
Press PRO to accept the data, then set the to SC CONT to CMC and the CMC MODE to FREE. The CMC will automatically proceed to P63.
P63 initially displays V06 N64, showing the current drag acceleration, velocity and range to splash. Key V16E to monitor this.
The program will mainly keep you updated with the drag acceleration, and will automatically move to P64 at 0.05g. The DAP will maintain a stable attitude.
Using orbital view, focus on the CM and use timescale until the CM passes the EI mark. P64 will start once 0.05g is detected.

When you are at the EI mark, ensure the GDC is aligned with the IMU by pressing GDC Align again and verify that FDAI 1 is equal to FDAI 2. The roll pointer on the EMS will now show you the correct up/down direction, and is used to maneuver through the atmosphere.

Set EMS mode to NORMAL. As AUTO ENTRY GUIDANCE is in development, you need to use manual control. Ensure the Rotational Hand Controllers have power and CMC is set to FREE. You will only need to control roll as the other axes are controlled by aerodynamic forces.
P64 will decide the next step based on many factors, such as vertical speed. For Earth Entry, it will move to P67.
When in P67, the roll is used to guide the capsules lift vector and towards the splashdown point. This is when the high G forces take place. The EMS will draw a line showing the G force and velocity.
If the roll index needle points up (your heads point down towards Earth), the lift vector points up and should reduce your G-load. Roll so the needle points up.

For beginners, leave it pointing up as you can not skip the atmosphere for Earth Entry and try to roll a maximum of 90 degrees to the left/right and learn how it works. In Lunar Entry you can and will skip if you only keep the lift vector pointing up.
Set the SC CONT to SCS as soon when the entry guidance is complete (P67 displays V16 N67). Check Landing checklist on the Mission Pad.
The chutes will soon deploy, starting with the drogue, then the main and then splashdown. This system is automatic, but can manually be controlled using the push buttons on MDC-1.
Drogue chute is deployed!
Main chute is out!

Good job today, there was a lot in this lesson, but it's a demanding phase. Please know we skipped many important steps and setup. The end of the Exam will be similar to this, but you will follow the mission pad checklists. But fear not, it is easier to follow the steps of the checklist compared to a chatty academy lesson.
This concludes the tutorial, feel free to watch it splash down as well. :)

Title: Lesson 9A - Atmospheric Entry
Description: Atmospheric Entry is a demanding phase of the mission. A lot of preparations are needed, and the last part of the spacecraft, the command module capsule, will make the final journey and splash down into the ocean. This lesson will use the SPS to set the trajectory back through the atmosphere, and the computer to guide the capsule through.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

Atmospheric Entry is the last phase of any Apollo Mission and must be carefully planned and executed.
It's an involved mission phase and it's important to double check the steps and the values.

In this lesson we will go through the steps needed to perform the entry burn using the SPS, then separate from the Service Module.
Using what's commonly referred to as the 60's, namely Program 61 - 67 on the Command Module computer, we can prepare the computer for entry.

P61 - Entry Preparation
P62 - CM/SM Separation and Preentry Maneuver
P63 - Entry - Initialization
P64 - Entry - post 0.05g
P65 - Entry - Up control
P66 - Entry - Ballistic
P67 - Final Phase

We will start orienting the CSM to retrograde direction, before using P30 and P40 to perform the needed burn.
Then we will follow checklists and set up the computer for entry.

The EMS, Entry Monitoring System, is heavily used during entry and will display the optimal entry path.

After the 60's, the parachute deployment sequence starts, before splashing down into the ocean.


Good luck!
